User-I-D and group-I-D gotchas.

This is the single most common bind-mount frustration. You mount your project in, and the container cannot write to it, or the files the container creates end up owned by root on your host. Understanding why makes the fixes obvious.

A container's processes run as some numeric user-I-D inside the namespace, and by default that is whatever the image's user instruction set, often root, sometimes a specific service user. When that process writes to a bind-mounted host path, the host records the write under that same numeric user-I-D, because by default docker does not remap I-Ds at all. User-namespace remapping is opt-in, and that is a notebook eight topic. So a container running as root writes files owned by root on your host, and a container running as some service user writes files owned by that number, which on your machine might map to a random local user or to nobody.

There are a few standard fixes. One is to match user-I-Ds, either running the container as your own host user with a user flag, or building the image so its user already matches yours, which is what dev-container setups do. Another, for development only, is to pre-create the host directory with permissive ownership before mounting it. A third is to prefer volumes over bind mounts where you can, because volume directories are owned by root on the host but the image's entry-point script can usually adjust ownership on first mount, which is exactly why most database images just work with volumes but fight you over bind mounts. And on mac and windows, docker desktop transparently translates ownership for bind mounts, which is one reason they feel normal there, though that abstraction leaks under heavy load.
